s diverse as David Walker, Frederick Douglass, Anna Julia Cooper, Ida B. Wells, W.E.B. Du Bois, Billie Holiday, and James Baldwin thought about the politics, people, character, and culture of a society that so often dominated them. Sharing a light of faith darkened but not extinguished by the tragic legacy of slavery, they resisted the conclusion that America would always be committed to white supremacy. They believed that democracy is always in the process of becoming and that they could use it to reimagine society. But they also saw that achieving racial justice wouldn’t absolve us of the darkest features of our shared past, and that democracy must be measured by how skillfully we confront a history that will forever remain with us.An ambitious account of the profound ways African Americans have reimagined democracy, The Darkened Light of Faith offers invaluable lessons about how to grapple with racial injustice and make democracy work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American leadershipxPhilosophy. 0aAfrican American leadershipzUnited States. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxPhilosophy. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governmentxPhilosophy. 0aDemocracyxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aPolitical sciencezUnited StatesxPhilosophy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAfrican American activists.  aAfrican American political thought.  aAfrican American.  aAmerican politics.  aBlack history.  aBlack politics.  aCornel West Imani Perry.  aDemocracy.  aEddie Glaude.  aIda B. Wells.  aJames Baldwin.  aMelvin L. Rogers.  aPolitical Thought.  aPrinceton University Press.  aPrinceton.  aRace Relations.  aRace, Democracy, and Freedom in African American Political Thought.  aRace.  aRacism.  aRep